"GitHub feels like a giant workshop where programmers store and collaborate on code. Almost everyone is confused the first time they use it."

We're going to start from here:

1. Learn what GitHub is (before clicking buttons).

• What is Git?
• What is GitHub?
• Repository (repo)
• Commit
• Branch
• Pull Request (PR)
• Issue
• Fork



2. Learn the interface. Explore a repository and identify:

_ 📁 Files
_ 📖 README
_ 📋 Issues
_ 🔀 Pull Requests
_ 💬 Discussions
_ ⭐ Star
_ 🍴 Fork



3. Practice with your own repository. Try to:

[]Create a repository
[]Upload a file
[]Edit a file
[]Commit changes
[]View your commit history



4. Contribute to open source. Once you're comfortable, learn how to:

+Fork a repository
+Create a branch
+Make changes
+Open a Pull Request




The best beginner-friendly resources are:

[GitHub Skills](https://skills.github.com?utm_source=chatgpt.com) — Interactive lessons that let you practice directly on GitHub.

[GitHub Docs](https://docs.github.com?utm_source=chatgpt.com) — The official documentation, including beginner guides.

[First Contributions](https://firstcontributions.github.io?utm_source=chatgpt.com) — A step-by-step tutorial for making your first open-source contribution.

[Oh My Git!](https://ohmygit.org?utm_source=chatgpt.com) — A free game that teaches Git concepts by playing.


One tip that helps: GitHub is like Google Drive + version history + collaboration for code. Every repository is a project, every commit is a saved version, and Pull Requests are how people propose changes.
